Clearly not. The creature simply whistled and tried to charge straight at Thassalin. Fortunately, despite its size, it was agile enough to dodge, but Nyssi couldn't help but scream when she nearly lost her grip on its overly smooth scales.
"HOW DO WE KILL THEM?" cried Nyssi.
"AIM FOR THEIR HEAD!"
"IT WON'T BE EASY!"
Thassalin blew, then circled around to get closer to the mountain he called his home. The black beast followed, somewhat frightened when a flash of fire hit it from behind. The creature hadn't noticed it was no longer alone. Its panic grew when Thassalin slowed down, then violently hit it on the head with his tail, causing it to veer off course.
Groaning and snarling, the creature gained altitude and spat into the air. Suddenly, everything became black, as if the monster was sucking the light from the sky and replacing it with a permanent cloud of eternal night.
With no visibility left, Thassalin tried to retreat, but scraped the tops of the trees before crashing into the clearing. As if it had known exactly where he had fallen, the creature charged straight at him, dragging the dark cloud behind it.
"Kayel!" exclaimed Tenuk as he emerged from the cloud and began flying in circles to try to locate Nyssi and Thassalin below, in the darkness. "What are we doing, Kayel? Kayel...? Kayel, where are you?"
Below, Nyssi struggled to get up. She was sure she had broken something, but her strange, entirely unnatural healing powers had already started to take effect. One could not say the same for Thassalin, who was lying on a mound, leaning against the only tree that had not bent under his weight. Nyssi did her best to try to reach Thassalin, but she could not see two meters in front of her. Everything was plunged into darkness, swallowed by the impious shadows. And within these shadows, something was howling.
A horrible, club-like tail struck beside Nyssi, knocking her over. She noted, however, that the tail was moving, not aiming for her. The creature, as much as Nyssi could see and hear, was snarling and clawing at the shadows it had created. Something was teleporting through the darkness, striking the monster, disorienting it.
A gunshot suddenly rang out, and the monster collapsed in silence, lifeless. The darkness surrounding them dissipated, revealing what had happened. Standing atop the creature was Kayel, holding the rifle and breathing heavily.
"It... was the strangest shadow jump I've ever made... Thanto kat'olon...", panted Kayel. His eyes glowed with a black light, and a dark energy coursed through his body. However, as he spoke, the organic plating of Kayel regained its color, and his eyes returned to their normal yellow.
It took Nyssi a moment to understand what had happened. They all knew that Kayel had strange shadow powers. He used them rarely, as most people considered them impious and rather frightening. But Nyssi did not know that Kayel could use these powers in the dark. And, judging by his behavior, Kayel seemed surprised as well.
"Are you okay?" Nyssi couldn't help but ask.
"Yes, I'm okay. I killed something. It'll get better in a minute." Kayel examined his work, while Tenuk made his way to land next to him, regaining his normal Spast form.
Now that the creature was no longer moving, they could better see what it was. Its skin was black as coal and slimy, but the saliva continued to stick to its body. It had four wings and four limbs, all ending in long claws, and two straight horns protruded from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what this thing was, something screamed and launched itself from a nearby bush. However, the beast did not have time to reach them, as a familiar vehicle crashed into its side, throwing it to the feet of Nyssi. Without taking any risks, she grabbed her rifle and immediately shot it in the head, killing the creature on the spot.
"Oops...", muttered Retvik from the driver's seat, before clumsily turning off the engine and jumping out of the truck. "I, uh, didn't mean to do that. Are you guys okay?"
"You almost missed all the action," regretted Tenuk. "Where were you?"
"You all let me down. I came here as fast as I could," sighed Retvik. "Can someone tell me what these nasty things are?"
The interrogation of Retvik fortunately received a response from Thassalin, who had just gotten up. He was all cut up and scratched all over and seemed a bit disoriented, but he didn't look too badly hurt.
"YOU KILLED THE CORRUPTED! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. CREATURES LEFT HERE WHEN THE CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS."
"You mean... the horrible monster god that we have... helped kill?", stammered Tenuk.
"YES. EXACTLY. THERE MAY BE OTHERS, BUT I DIDN'T MANAGE TO AIM FOR THEIR HEADS. I MISS A RIFLE. PLUS, TWO AGAINST ONE, IT'S NOT FAIR, IS IT?" Thassalin walked toward Kayel and patted his head. "THANK YOU, KID. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. BUT LESS MURDEROUS AND LESS ABLE TO KILL UNIVERSES."
"Um... thank you... I guess," said Kayel with a shrug. "So, are we done here?"
Nyssi shrugged, then picked up her camera to take photos of the now-dead creatures. She then pulled out her favorite dagger, the god of death's blade, and began cutting off one of the creature's horns, then moving on to the other. But as she finished, the creatures burst into flames and quickly turned into piles of ash. The same thing happened to the horns Nyssi had cut off.
"Well... it's both convenient and completely inconvenient," she sighed. "At least I still have the photos..."
